{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] | image = Gilles Gaston Granger (Epistémologie, CNAM-Paris) - Archives Philippe Binant.jpg | caption = Gilles Gaston Granger at the [[Conservatoire national des arts et métiers]], Paris, 2000. | name = Gilles-Gaston Granger | birth_date = 28 January 1920 | birth_place = Paris | death_date = 24 August 2016 | death_place = | alma_mater = [[École Normale Supérieure]] | institutions = [[Collège de France]] (1986–1990) | school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]]<ref>Alan D. Schrift (2006), ''Twentieth-Century French Philosophy: Key Themes and Thinkers'', Blackwell Publishing, p. 76.</ref> | main_interests = [[Philosophical logic]], [[philosophy of science]], [[epistemology]] | influences = [[Jean Cavaillès]], [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] | influenced = [[Jules Vuillemin]], [[Jacques Bouveresse]] | notable_ideas = Philosophy of [[Style (sociolinguistics)|style]] }} '''Gilles-Gaston<ref>Usually written "Gilles Gaston" in French. "Gilles" was his alias in the Resistance, which he kept after the war. [[Claudine Tiercelin]], [http://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2016/09/05/la-mort-du-philosophe-gilles-gaston-granger_4992901_3382.html "La mort du philosophe Gilles-Gaston Granger"], ''Le Monde'', 5 September 2016.]</ref> Granger''' ({{IPAc-en|ɡ|r|ɑː|n|ˈ|ʒ|eɪ}}; {{IPA-fr|ɡʁɑ̃ʒe|lang}}; 28 January 1920 – 24 August 2016) was a French [[philosopher]].
==Work== His works discuss the philosophy of [[Philosophical logic|logic]], [[Philosophy of mathematics|mathematics]], [[Social science|human and social sciences]], [[Aristotle]], [[Jean Cavaillès]], [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]]. He produced the most authoritative<ref>[[Gallimard]] had published a first translation by [[Pierre Klossowski]] but later published Granger's translation.</ref> French translation of Wittgenstein's ''[[Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus]]'' and published more than 150 scientific articles.<ref name=bibliography/>
In 1968 he co-founded with [[Jules Vuillemin]] the journal ''L'Âge de la Science''.<ref name=bibliography>[http://poincare.univ-lorraine.fr/sites/poincare.univ-lorraine.fr/files/users/documents/fichier_page/biblio_vuillemin.pdf Bibliography].</ref> He was president of the scientific committee of Jules Vuillemin's Archives.<ref>[http://poincare.univ-lorraine.fr/fr/comite-scientifique-des-archives-jules-vuillemin Jules Vuillemin's Archives.]</ref>
