The '''metakosmia''' ({{lang-grc-gre|μετακόσμια}}; {{lang-la|intermundia}}), according to [[Epicurean]] philosophy were the relatively empty spaces in the [[Infinity|infinite]] [[Vacuum|void]] where worlds had not been formed by the joining together of the [[atoms]] through their endless motion. [[Epicurus]] held that the metakosmia were the abode of the [[god]]s, whom he considered to be immortal and blissful living beings made of atoms.
